# Akasha ontology — namespace: tale
# atoms: 276

def "tale:aesop_ant_dove" "An ant that has fallen into a stream is saved when a dove drops a leaf for it to climb onto. Later, seeing a hunter take aim at the dove, the ant bites his heel, spoiling the shot and saving its friend. Moral: one good turn deserves another. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_ant_dove fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_ant_dove gratitude @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_ant_dove reciprocity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_ant_dove tale:aesop_lion_mouse @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_ant_dove"

def "tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper" "Through the summer the grasshopper sings while the ant toils to store grain. When winter comes the starving grasshopper begs from the ant, who asks what it did all season. Moral: prepare today for the needs of tomorrow. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper prudence @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper foresight @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper tale:aesop_tortoise_hare @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper"

def "tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin" "An ass dons a lion's skin and frightens the other animals, until it brays and is recognized and beaten. Moral: borrowed grandeur is undone by one's own nature. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin pretension @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin vanity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin"

def "tale:aesop_bat_birds_beasts" "In the war between the birds and the beasts, the bat sides with whichever seems to be winning, claiming now to be a bird, now a beast. When peace is made, both sides shun it, and it flies only by night. Moral: he who plays both sides ends trusted by neither. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_bat_birds_beasts fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_bat_birds_beasts opportunism @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_bat_birds_beasts loyalty @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_bat_birds_beasts"

def "tale:aesop_belling_cat" "The mice agree that a bell on the cat would warn them of its approach, but when it comes to hanging it, none of them will volunteer. Moral: it is easy to propose what is hard to perform. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_belling_cat fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_belling_cat impracticality @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_belling_cat courage @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_belling_cat"

def "tale:aesop_boy_cried_wolf" "A shepherd boy amuses himself by falsely shouting that a wolf is attacking, drawing villagers who find nothing. When a wolf truly comes, no one heeds his cries. Moral: a liar will not be believed even when telling the truth. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_boy_cried_wolf fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_boy_cried_wolf honesty @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_boy_cried_wolf trust @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_boy_cried_wolf"

def "tale:aesop_boy_filberts" "A boy reaches into a jar for filberts and grabs a fistful so large he cannot draw his hand back out; rather than let some go, he weeps. Moral: do not attempt too much at once; take a moderate share and you will succeed. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_boy_filberts fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_boy_filberts moderation @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_boy_filberts greed @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_boy_filberts"

def "tale:aesop_bundle_sticks" "A dying father shows his quarreling sons that a bundle of sticks cannot be broken together, though each stick snaps easily alone. Moral: in unity there is strength. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_bundle_sticks fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_bundle_sticks cooperation @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_bundle_sticks unity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_bundle_sticks"

def "tale:aesop_cat_fox" "The fox boasts of a hundred tricks for escaping the hounds; the cat knows only one. When the dogs come, the cat climbs a tree at once, while the fox, hesitating among its many schemes, is caught. Moral: one sure plan is worth a hundred uncertain ones. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_cat_fox fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_cat_fox focus @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_cat_fox reliability @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_cat_fox"

def "tale:aesop_crow_pitcher" "A thirsty crow finds a pitcher with water too low to reach. It drops in pebbles one by one until the water rises to its beak. Moral: necessity is the mother of invention; little by little does the trick. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_crow_pitcher fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_crow_pitcher ingenuity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_crow_pitcher persistence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_crow_pitcher"

def "tale:aesop_crow_swan" "A crow, envying the swan's white plumage, leaves its home to live upon the water and wash itself; but its feathers stay black and it starves for want of its proper food. Moral: a change of place does not change one's nature. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_crow_swan fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_crow_swan nature @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_crow_swan futility @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_crow_swan"

def "tale:aesop_dog_manger" "A dog lies in a manger of hay it cannot eat, snarling to keep the hungry ox from eating it either. Moral: some begrudge others what they themselves cannot use. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_dog_manger fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_dog_manger spite @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_dog_manger selfishness @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_dog_manger"

def "tale:aesop_dog_reflection" "Crossing a stream with meat in its jaws, a dog sees its reflection and, mistaking it for another dog with a larger piece, snaps at it and drops its own meat into the water. Moral: in grasping at shadows one loses the substance. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_dog_reflection fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_dog_reflection greed @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_dog_reflection envy @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_dog_reflection"

def "tale:aesop_dog_wolf" "A lean wolf admires a sleek house-dog and is invited to share its easy life, until it notices the worn mark of a collar on the dog's neck. Learning that it must be chained, the wolf chooses hunger and freedom over comfort and a chain. Moral: better lean liberty than fat servitude. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_dog_wolf fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_dog_wolf freedom @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_dog_wolf independence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_dog_wolf"

def "tale:aesop_eagle_arrow" "Struck down by an arrow, the eagle looks at the shaft and sees that it is fledged with one of its own feathers. Moral: we often furnish the means of our own destruction. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_eagle_arrow fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_eagle_arrow self_destruction @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_eagle_arrow irony @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_eagle_arrow"

def "tale:aesop_fox_crow" "A crow with cheese in its beak is flattered by a fox praising its voice. Opening its beak to sing, the crow drops the cheese, which the fox snatches up. Moral: do not trust flatterers. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_fox_crow fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_fox_crow flattery @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_crow vanity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_crow cunning @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_fox_crow"

def "tale:aesop_fox_goat_well" "A fox trapped in a well persuades a thirsty goat to jump in, then climbs out upon the goat's back, leaving it stranded below. Moral: look before you leap, and never trust the counsel of one already in difficulty. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_fox_goat_well fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_fox_goat_well caution @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_goat_well deception @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_goat_well cunning @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_fox_goat_well"

def "tale:aesop_fox_grapes" "A hungry fox leaps again and again for a cluster of grapes hanging out of reach. Failing, it walks away declaring the grapes were sour anyway. Moral: it is easy to despise what you cannot have. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_fox_grapes fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_fox_grapes rationalization @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_grapes cunning @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_fox_grapes"

def "tale:aesop_fox_lion" "The first time the fox saw the lion it was nearly frightened to death; the second time it merely trembled; the third time it walked up and spoke with him without fear. Moral: familiarity breeds contempt. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_fox_lion fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_fox_lion familiarity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_lion fear @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_fox_lion"

def "tale:aesop_fox_stork" "A fox serves the stork soup in a flat dish from which it cannot drink; the stork returns the invitation and serves food in a tall narrow jar the fox cannot reach. Moral: treat others as you would be treated. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_fox_stork fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_fox_stork reciprocity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_fox_stork cunning @related_to
ln tale:aesop_fox_stork golden_rule calc:associated_with
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_fox_stork"

def "tale:aesop_frog_ox" "A frog, envying the great bulk of an ox, puffs itself up larger and larger to match it, until it bursts. Moral: vanity that overreaches its nature ends in ruin. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_frog_ox fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_frog_ox vanity @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_frog_ox hubris @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_frog_ox"

def "tale:aesop_frogs_king" "The frogs, weary of having no ruler, beg Zeus for a king. He drops a log into their pond, but they soon scorn its stillness and demand a real king; he sends a water-snake, which devours them. Moral: be careful what you wish for — an idle ruler is better than a cruel one. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_frogs_king fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_frogs_king discontent @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_frogs_king governance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_frogs_king"

def "tale:aesop_goatherd_goats" "A goatherd shelters some wild goats with his own and, hoping to keep them, feeds the newcomers the better fare. When the storm clears the wild goats run off, saying that since he favored strangers over his old flock, he would surely do the same to them. Moral: neglect the old for the new and you will keep neither. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_goatherd_goats fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_goatherd_goats loyalty @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_goatherd_goats neglect @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_goatherd_goats"

def "tale:aesop_golden_goose" "A couple owns a goose that lays one golden egg each day. Greedy for all the gold at once, they kill the goose and find nothing within. Moral: greed destroys the very source of its plenty. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_golden_goose fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_golden_goose greed @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_golden_goose overreach @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_golden_goose"

def "tale:aesop_hares_frogs" "The timid hares, despairing of their fearful lives, resolve to drown themselves; but as they reach the pond, the frogs leap away in still greater terror of them. Moral: there is always someone worse off than yourself. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_hares_frogs fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_hares_frogs perspective @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_hares_frogs courage @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_hares_frogs"

def "tale:aesop_hercules_wagoner" "A wagoner whose cart is mired in mud prays to Hercules for help; the god tells him to put his own shoulder to the wheel. Moral: the gods help those who help themselves. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_hercules_wagoner fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_hercules_wagoner self_reliance @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_hercules_wagoner effort @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_hercules_wagoner"

def "tale:aesop_heron" "A heron walks the riverbank too proud to eat the small fish, certain that finer fare will come. As the day wanes and the fish move off, it is glad at last to make its meal of a single snail. Moral: do not be over-fastidious, lest you be left with nothing. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_heron fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_heron fastidiousness @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_heron opportunity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_heron"

def "tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox" "A lion and a bear seize the same fawn and fight over it until both lie wounded and exhausted. A fox, who has watched from nearby, slips between them and carries off the prize. Moral: while two contend, a third runs off with the gain. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox opportunism @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox conflict @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox"

def "tale:aesop_lion_mouse" "A lion spares a tiny mouse that begged for its life. Later, caught in a hunter's net, the lion is freed when the grateful mouse gnaws through the ropes. Moral: no act of kindness is ever wasted, and the small may aid the great. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_lion_mouse fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_lion_mouse gratitude @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_lion_mouse mercy @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_lion_mouse"

def "tale:aesop_lion_statue" "A man and a lion dispute which of them is the stronger, and the man points to a statue of a man overcoming a lion. The lion replies that if lions could carve, the lion would stand on top. Moral: the story changes with the one who tells it. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_lion_statue fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_lion_statue perspective @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_lion_statue narrative @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_lion_statue"

def "tale:aesop_lions_share" "A lion hunts alongside other beasts, then divides the prey and claims every portion by right of being lion. Moral: the powerful may seize all and call it justice. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_lions_share fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_lions_share power @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_lions_share injustice @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_lions_share"

def "tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail" "Carrying milk to market, a maid daydreams of the profit, the eggs, the fine dress, until, tossing her head in imagined pride, she spills the pail. Moral: do not count your chickens before they are hatched. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail overconfidence @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail daydreaming @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail"

def "tale:aesop_mountain_labour" "A mountain groans and heaves as though to bring forth something vast; the crowd gathers in awe, and out creeps a single mouse. Moral: great threats often end in small results. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_mountain_labour fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_mountain_labour exaggeration @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_mountain_labour anticlimax @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_mountain_labour"

def "tale:aesop_north_wind_sun" "The North Wind and the Sun dispute who is stronger and test it on a traveler's cloak. The harder the wind blows, the tighter the man clings to it; the sun's gentle warmth makes him take it off. Moral: gentle persuasion succeeds where force fails. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_north_wind_sun fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_north_wind_sun persuasion @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_north_wind_sun gentleness @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_north_wind_sun"

def "tale:aesop_oak_reed" "An oak proud of its strength mocks the reeds that bend to every breeze. A great storm uproots the rigid oak, while the yielding reeds bow and survive. Moral: the flexible endure where the unbending break. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_oak_reed fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_oak_reed adaptability @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_oak_reed humility @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_oak_reed"

def "tale:aesop_old_man_death" "An old man, weary under a load of sticks, throws it down and calls aloud for Death. When Death appears and asks his wish, the frightened man says only that he wants help lifting the load again. Moral: however hard life is, we cling to it. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_old_man_death fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_old_man_death mortality @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_old_man_death fear @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_old_man_death"

def "tale:aesop_peacock_crane" "The peacock mocks the crane for its dull gray feathers, boasting of its own gold and purple. The crane answers that it soars among the stars while the peacock struts on the ground like a barnyard fowl. Moral: useful plainness outranks useless splendor. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_peacock_crane fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_peacock_crane substance @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_peacock_crane vanity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_peacock_crane"

def "tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle" "A tortoise, longing to fly, begs an eagle to carry it aloft. The eagle warns that it is not made for the air, but bears it up and lets go, and the tortoise is dashed upon the rocks below. Moral: be content with your nature; overreaching ends in ruin. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle overreach @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle contentment @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle tale:aesop_frog_ox @related_to
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle"

def "tale:aesop_tortoise_hare" "A swift hare ridicules a tortoise for its slowness and agrees to race it. Certain of winning, the hare stops to nap; the tortoise plods on without pausing and crosses the line first. Moral: slow and steady wins the race. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_hare fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_hare perseverance @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_tortoise_hare complacency @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_tortoise_hare"

def "tale:aesop_town_country_mouse" "A town mouse visits its country cousin, scorns the plain fare, and invites it to the city's feasts. But the constant danger of cats and men drives the country mouse home, preferring simple safety to luxury in fear. Moral: better plain bread in peace than a feast in fear. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_town_country_mouse fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_town_country_mouse contentment @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_town_country_mouse simplicity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_town_country_mouse"

def "tale:aesop_two_pots" "Two pots, one of brass and one of clay, are swept down a river together. The brass pot urges the clay one to keep close, but the clay pot fears that any touch between them would shatter it. Moral: avoid the company of the powerful, for the weak suffer most from the contact. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_two_pots fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_two_pots prudence @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_two_pots inequality @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_two_pots"

def "tale:aesop_wolf_crane" "A wolf with a bone lodged in its throat promises a reward to any who removes it. The crane puts its long head down the wolf's throat and draws the bone out; when it asks for the reward, the wolf says the reward is that the crane took its head from a wolf's jaws unbitten. Moral: in serving the wicked, expect no reward, and be glad to escape unhurt. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_wolf_crane fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_wolf_crane ingratitude @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_wolf_crane prudence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_wolf_crane"

def "tale:aesop_wolf_lamb" "A wolf wishing to eat a lamb drinking downstream accuses it of fouling the water and of other invented offenses, then devours it regardless. Moral: the tyrant will always find a pretext. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_wolf_lamb fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_wolf_lamb injustice @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_wolf_lamb tyranny @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_wolf_lamb"

def "tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing" "A wolf wraps itself in a fleece to pass unnoticed among the flock and prey on the sheep. Moral: appearances deceive; an enemy may wear a friendly guise. — Aesop"
ln tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing fable sys:is_a
ln tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing deception @illustrates
ln tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing disguise @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.aesop_fables" id="tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing"

def "tale:anansi_bald_head" "At his mother-in-law's funeral feast, Anansi, too greedy to wait, hides hot beans under his hat to eat in secret. Pressed to remove his hat out of respect, he refuses, sweating and squirming, until the scalding beans force the hat off — and the beans take every hair with them. Moral: greed unmasks itself, and leaves its mark. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_bald_head folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_bald_head greed @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_bald_head comeuppance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_bald_head"

def "tale:anansi_moss_rock" "Anansi discovers a strange moss-covered rock that knocks senseless anyone who remarks on it, and uses it to rob the other animals of their food, sending each to admire the rock and stealing their share as they lie stunned. But Little Bush Deer, who has watched, leads Anansi to the rock and prompts him to speak the fatal words, and Anansi falls senseless while she empties his stores. Moral: the trap you set for others is laid open for yourself. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_moss_rock folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_moss_rock greed @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_moss_rock comeuppance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_moss_rock"

def "tale:anansi_stories" "Anansi longs to own all the world's stories, hoarded by the Sky-God Nyame, who names an impossible price: the python, the leopard, the hornets, and the unseen forest dwarf. By wit alone Anansi captures each — measuring the python on a pole, trapping the leopard in a pit, luring the hornets into a gourd with a feigned rain — and Nyame grants him the stories, which ever after are called Anansi stories. Moral: cunning can buy what gold and strength cannot. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_stories folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_stories wit @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_stories origin @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_stories"

def "tale:anansi_talking_skull" "Wandering, a man finds a skull that speaks, saying its own mouth brought it to this place; amazed, the man boasts to the king of a talking skull, on pain of death if it proves false. Brought before the court, the skull stays silent, and the man is executed — whereupon the skull speaks at last: a mouth brought you here, just as a mouth brought me. Moral: idle boasting digs its own grave. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_talking_skull folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_talking_skull foolish_speech @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_talking_skull"

def "tale:anansi_tar_baby" "Something keeps stealing from Anansi's garden, so he shapes a figure of sticky gum and sets it to watch. In the night the thief — or Anansi himself, in the tellings where the trick rebounds — demands the silent figure answer, and strikes it in anger; fist and foot stick fast, blow after blow, until the striker is held helpless by the gum. Moral: it is wounded pride, not the trap, that holds us fastest. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_tar_baby folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_tar_baby temper @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_tar_baby pride @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_tar_baby tale:kancil_sticky_figure @parallels
