def "tale:anansi_turtle_dinner" "Turtle arrives at dinner time and Anansi, loath to share, insists Turtle wash his dusty hands first; each time Turtle returns from the river the food is lower, until Anansi has eaten it all. Turtle later invites Anansi to dine at the river bottom, where Anansi, unable to sink, watches helplessly as Turtle eats below. Moral: the trick you play returns to you in kind. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_turtle_dinner folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_turtle_dinner reciprocity @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_turtle_dinner deception @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_turtle_dinner tale:aesop_fox_stork @parallels
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_turtle_dinner"

def "tale:anansi_wisdom_pot" "Anansi gathers all the world's wisdom into a great pot to keep for himself, and tries to climb a tree to hide it, clutching the pot against his belly so that he cannot grip. His small son calls out to tie it on his back instead — and Anansi, enraged that wisdom remains in the world despite his hoarding, dashes the pot to pieces, scattering wisdom everywhere for everyone. Moral: wisdom cannot be hoarded; that is why all people share in it. — Anansi folktale"
ln tale:anansi_wisdom_pot folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:anansi_wisdom_pot pride @illustrates
ln tale:anansi_wisdom_pot origin @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.anansi_tales" id="tale:anansi_wisdom_pot"

def "tale:arabian_ali_baba" "Ali Baba overhears the words 'Open Sesame' that unlock the forty thieves' treasure cave and takes a modest share. His greedy brother Cassim, having forced the secret from him, gorges on the gold but forgets the magic words, is trapped inside, and is killed. When the thieves track Ali Baba home, his quick-witted servant Morgiana foils them — scalding the men hidden in oil jars and slaying their captain in a dance. Moral: greed forgets the way out; level wit finds it. — Thousand and One Nights"
ln tale:arabian_ali_baba folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:arabian_ali_baba greed @illustrates
ln tale:arabian_ali_baba cleverness @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.arabian_tales" id="tale:arabian_ali_baba"

def "tale:arabian_ass_and_ox" "An ox, worn out by the plow, takes the ass's advice to refuse its food and feign sickness for a day's rest. Pleased with the result, the ox does it again — but the farmer, told the ox is ill, yokes the idle ass to the plow in its place. The ass, now laboring under its own clever counsel, hastens to advise the ox to recover at once. Moral: advice given to spare another may fall back upon the giver. — Thousand and One Nights"
ln tale:arabian_ass_and_ox folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:arabian_ass_and_ox meddling @illustrates
ln tale:arabian_ass_and_ox cunning @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.arabian_tales" id="tale:arabian_ass_and_ox"

def "tale:arabian_envious_and_envied" "One man so envies his pious neighbor's good name that he tries to drown him in a well; but the well shelters spirits who heal the envied man and grant him fortune, while the envier, scheming on, is undone by his own malice. Moral: envy labors hardest to ruin itself. — Thousand and One Nights"
ln tale:arabian_envious_and_envied folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:arabian_envious_and_envied envy @illustrates
ln tale:arabian_envious_and_envied comeuppance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.arabian_tales" id="tale:arabian_envious_and_envied"

def "tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni" "A poor fisherman hauls up a sealed brass jar and opens it, releasing a jinni imprisoned for centuries — who, soured by his long captivity, vows to kill his rescuer. The fisherman feigns disbelief that so vast a being could ever have fit in so small a jar; stung, the jinni dissolves back inside to prove it, and the fisherman claps the seal shut. Moral: where strength would fail, doubt and wit prevail. — Thousand and One Nights"
ln tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni ingratitude @illustrates
ln tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni wit @illustrates
ln tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile @parallels
set.add name="ontology.arabian_tales" id="tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni"

def "tale:arabian_merchant_jinni" "A merchant idly tosses a date-stone and unknowingly kills the unseen son of a jinni, who appears to claim his life in return. Three passing sheikhs each offer to tell the jinni a tale so wondrous that, if it pleases him, he will pardon a third of the merchant's blood — and by their stories the merchant is spared. Moral: a well-told tale can buy back a life. — Thousand and One Nights"
