def "tale:japan_bunbuku_chagama" "A poor man frees a trapped tanuki, which in gratitude turns itself into a fine tea-kettle for him to sell to a temple. Half-transformed and unable to bear the priest's scrubbing and fire, it flees back to the man, who exhibits it as a tightrope-walking, dancing kettle and prospers, sharing his fortune with his strange friend. Moral: a kindness freely given comes back transformed. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_bunbuku_chagama folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_bunbuku_chagama gratitude @illustrates
ln tale:japan_bunbuku_chagama transformation @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_bunbuku_chagama"

def "tale:japan_hanasaka_jiisan" "A gentle old couple's dog leads them to buried gold; a greedy neighbor borrows the dog, finds only filth, and kills it. From the dog's grave grows a tree that yields a magic mortar, and from its ashes the kind man makes withered cherry trees burst into bloom before a lord, winning reward — while the neighbor, copying him, blinds the lord with ash and is punished. Moral: kindness blossoms; envious mimicry withers. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_hanasaka_jiisan folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_hanasaka_jiisan kindness @illustrates
ln tale:japan_hanasaka_jiisan imitation @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_hanasaka_jiisan"

def "tale:japan_kachikachi_yama" "A wicked tanuki kills a farmer's wife and mocks the grieving old man; the couple's friend, a rabbit, takes up their cause. The rabbit sets fire to the load on the tanuki's back, treats the burns with a stinging paste, and lures him onto a boat of mud that dissolves beneath him, drowning the murderer. Moral: cruelty earns a patient and exacting justice. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_kachikachi_yama folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_kachikachi_yama justice @illustrates
ln tale:japan_kachikachi_yama cunning @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_kachikachi_yama"

def "tale:japan_kobutori_jiisan" "An old man with a lump on his cheek shelters from rain and delights a band of revelling oni with his dancing; charmed, they take his lump as a 'pledge' to ensure his return — freeing him of it. His neighbor, lumped on the other cheek, dances clumsily; the disgusted oni return the first man's lump, and he goes home with two. Moral: a glad and willing heart is rewarded; grudging imitation doubles the burden. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_kobutori_jiisan folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_kobutori_jiisan sincerity @illustrates
ln tale:japan_kobutori_jiisan imitation @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_kobutori_jiisan"

def "tale:japan_nezumi_yomeiri" "A pair of mice, seeking the mightiest husband in the world for their daughter, go first to the Sun — who yields to the Cloud that hides him, who yields to the Wind that scatters it, who yields to the Wall that stops it, who yields to the Mouse that gnaws it through. So they wed their daughter to a mouse after all. Moral: each power has its master, and one's own kind may be the strongest match. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_nezumi_yomeiri folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_nezumi_yomeiri humility @illustrates
ln tale:japan_nezumi_yomeiri perspective @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_nezumi_yomeiri"

def "tale:japan_saru_kani" "A sly monkey cheats a crab, swapping a quick-eaten rice ball for a persimmon seed; the crab patiently raises the seed into a fruited tree, but the monkey steals the ripe fruit and pelts the crab to death with hard ones. The crab's children, with a chestnut, a wasp, a mortar, and cow-dung, ambush the monkey in turn and avenge their parent. Moral: the small and weak, banded together, bring the bully to account. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_saru_kani folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_saru_kani cooperation @illustrates
ln tale:japan_saru_kani justice @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_saru_kani"

def "tale:japan_shitakiri_suzume" "A kind old man tends a sparrow whose tongue his spiteful wife has cut; visiting its home, he is offered a large basket or a small one and humbly takes the small, which proves full of treasure. The greedy wife demands the large basket and hauls it home stuffed with snakes and demons. Moral: a modest, kind heart is repaid; greed carries home its own punishment. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_shitakiri_suzume folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_shitakiri_suzume kindness @illustrates
ln tale:japan_shitakiri_suzume greed @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_shitakiri_suzume"

def "tale:japan_urashima_taro" "The fisherman Urashima Tarō rescues a tormented turtle and is borne beneath the sea to the Dragon Palace, where he passes what seems a few happy days. Returning home, he finds lifetimes have gone by and all he knew is dust; opening the forbidden box his host gave him, he releases the years he had escaped, and in an instant becomes an aged man. Moral: time cannot be cheated, and the forbidden box is best left shut. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_urashima_taro folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_urashima_taro time @illustrates
ln tale:japan_urashima_taro curiosity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_urashima_taro"

def "tale:japan_warashibe_choja" "A poor man, told by Kannon to treasure the first thing he grasps, leaves the temple clutching a single straw. To the straw he ties a horsefly, which delights a crying child; trading up by chance and kindness — straw for oranges, oranges for cloth, cloth for a horse, the horse for a house and fields — he becomes a wealthy man. Moral: humble beginnings, met with honesty and goodwill, may compound into fortune. — Japanese folktale"
ln tale:japan_warashibe_choja folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:japan_warashibe_choja providence @illustrates
ln tale:japan_warashibe_choja humility @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.japan_tales" id="tale:japan_warashibe_choja"

def "tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin" "A trader dresses his ass in a lion's skin and turns it loose to graze by night in others' fields, where folk flee the supposed lion. All goes well until the ass, hearing other asses, brays in answer; the villagers know the voice, strip off the skin, and beat it. Moral: the disguise is undone by the voice within. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin false_identity @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin pretension @illustrates
