set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin"

def "tale:jataka_banyan_deer" "A king fond of venison spares a golden deer-king on the terms that the herds send one deer to the block each day. When the lot falls on a pregnant doe, the deer-king, the Bodhisattva, offers his own neck in her place. Struck by such compassion, the king spares the deer-king, the doe, and at last all the deer — and all creatures — from the hunt. Moral: one act of selfless mercy can win mercy for all. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_banyan_deer fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_banyan_deer compassion @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_banyan_deer self_sacrifice @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_banyan_deer bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_banyan_deer"

def "tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant" "The Bodhisattva is a great six-tusked elephant. A queen, nursing a grudge from a former life, sends a hunter to bring back his tusks. Mortally wounded, the elephant sees the hunter cannot saw through the ivory, and with his own trunk helps cut and gives his tusks freely, bearing no anger even at his death. Moral: the truly great answer cruelty with compassion. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant compassion @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant self_sacrifice @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_chaddanta_elephant"

def "tale:jataka_crane_crab" "A crane, too old to fish, tells the fish of a coming drought and offers to carry them to a fine deep lake, but eats each one behind a rock. When a wary crab asks to be carried, it loops its claws about the crane's neck; finding the heap of bones, it grips tight and beheads the deceiver. Moral: the trickster meets his end in the one he cannot deceive. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_crane_crab fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_crane_crab deceit @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_crane_crab greed @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_crane_crab tale:panchatantra_heron_crab @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_crane_crab"

def "tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters" "Two otters quarrel over a great fish they have caught together, one having seized the head, the other the tail. They ask a passing jackal to divide it; he gravely awards the head to one and the tail to the other — and takes the fat middle as his judge's fee, trotting off to feed his family. Moral: when the greedy will not share, the arbiter eats the best of it. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters conflict @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters opportunism @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_dabbhapuppha_otters"

def "tale:jataka_elephant_dog_friends" "A great royal elephant befriends a stray dog, and the two eat and play together inseparably. When the dog is sold away, the elephant pines, refusing food and water, until the king sends for the dog; reunited, the elephant lifts his friend tenderly with his trunk, and both thrive again. Moral: the heart, even the mightiest, withers without its friend. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_elephant_dog_friends fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_elephant_dog_friends friendship @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_elephant_dog_friends"

def "tale:jataka_foolish_son_gnat" "A foolish son, seeing a gnat settle on his sleeping father's bald head, takes up a heavy axe to kill it and splits his father's skull instead. Moral: a foolish friend does more harm than a thoughtful foe. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_foolish_son_gnat fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_foolish_son_gnat folly @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_foolish_son_gnat tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_foolish_son_gnat"

def "tale:jataka_gardener_monkeys" "When the royal gardeners take a holiday, they ask the troop of monkeys living in the park to water the young trees. The monkeys, meaning to be thorough, pull up each sapling to judge its roots and give the deeper-rooted ones more water — and so kill every tree they tend. Moral: well-meant help without wisdom is ruin. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_gardener_monkeys fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_gardener_monkeys folly @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_gardener_monkeys misguided_effort @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_gardener_monkeys"

def "tale:jataka_golden_goose" "A man reborn as a golden goose provides for his former wife and daughters by letting them pluck one golden feather at a time. Growing greedy, the wife seizes the goose and plucks out every feather at once; but the feathers, torn against the bird's will, turn to plain plumage, and the goose flies off, leaving them poor. Moral: grasp for all at once and you lose even what was freely given. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_golden_goose fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_golden_goose greed @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_golden_goose contentment @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_golden_goose tale:aesop_golden_goose @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_golden_goose"

def "tale:jataka_jackal_crow_flattery" "A jackal beneath a rose-apple tree praises a crow feasting above as sweet-voiced and noble, that the crow may shower him with fruit; the crow, flattered, calls the jackal the finest of beasts, and down come the rose-apples. A passing sage observes that liar praises liar — two frauds trading hollow compliments. Moral: where flatterer flatters flatterer, only fraud is fed. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_jackal_crow_flattery fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_jackal_crow_flattery flattery @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_jackal_crow_flattery tale:aesop_fox_crow @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_jackal_crow_flattery"

def "tale:jataka_merchant_seri" "Two peddlers cross a river town. The greedy one, offered an old blackened bowl by a poor girl, cheats her to seize it for nothing, knowing it is solid gold; but he delays to drive a harder bargain. The honest peddler, the Bodhisattva, comes after, deals fairly, and wins the golden bowl. Moral: greed that overreaches loses to honest dealing. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_merchant_seri fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_merchant_seri honesty @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_merchant_seri greed @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_merchant_seri bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_merchant_seri"

def "tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile" "A monkey living in a riverside tree befriends a crocodile and shares fruit with him, until the crocodile's wife craves the monkey's heart. Offered a ride across the river and then told the plan midstream, the monkey says calmly that monkeys keep their hearts hung in the fig tree and must fetch it; carried back to the bank, he springs up the tree and is safe. Moral: a cool head escapes the jaws of treachery. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile wit @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile presence_of_mind @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile bodhisattva @related_to
ln tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile"

def "tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge" "Hunters corner a troop of monkeys on a mango tree by a river. Their king, the Bodhisattva, stretches his own body from the tree to the far bank to make a living bridge, and the whole troop crosses to safety over his back. Crushed and dying, he is lifted down by the watching human king, to whom he teaches that a ruler's first duty is the welfare of his people, before his own life. Moral: true leadership spends itself for those it guards. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge self_sacrifice @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge leadership @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge compassion @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_monkey_king_bridge"

def "tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea" "A troop of monkeys is given a handful of peas, and one drops a single pea while climbing. Letting fall the whole fistful to chase the one that rolled away, he ends with nothing at all. Moral: he who lets go everything to grasp at one lost thing keeps neither. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea greed @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea folly @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea tale:aesop_boy_filberts @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_monkey_one_pea"

def "tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox" "The Bodhisattva is a mighty ox who offers to win his poor master a wager by hauling a hundred loaded carts. But when the master, before the crowd, curses and goads him as a rogue, the ox stands still in shame, and the bet is lost. Spoken to gently and praised the next time, he pulls the carts with ease and doubles the winnings. Moral: harsh words break even the willing; kind words move mountains. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox kindness @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox speech @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_nandivisala_ox"

def "tale:jataka_partridge_elders" "A partridge, a monkey, and an elephant, living under a great banyan, fall to disputing who is eldest and so most deserving of respect. By recalling the size of the tree in their earliest memories, they find the partridge is oldest; thereafter they honor one another by seniority and live in harmony, and their concord becomes known far and wide. Moral: where elders are honored, peace and order follow. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_partridge_elders fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_partridge_elders respect @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_partridge_elders harmony @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_partridge_elders bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_partridge_elders"

def "tale:jataka_patient_buffalo" "A great buffalo, the Bodhisattva, is plagued by an impudent monkey that clambers on him, jabs him, and fouls his food, yet he bears it all without anger. When a spirit asks why he tolerates such insolence, he answers that patience practiced toward the weak and rude is patience indeed, and that the monkey will earn its own reckoning elsewhere. Moral: forbearance toward the provoking is the truest strength. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_patient_buffalo fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_patient_buffalo patience @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_patient_buffalo forbearance @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_patient_buffalo bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_patient_buffalo"

def "tale:jataka_quail_falcon" "A quail keeps to a ploughed field of clods and furrows that is its own ground. A falcon mocks it and stoops to seize it; the quail darts behind a great clod, and the falcon, striking at full speed, dashes itself to death against the earth. Moral: keep to your own ground, where even the strong cannot reach you. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_quail_falcon fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_quail_falcon prudence @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_quail_falcon home_ground @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_quail_falcon"

def "tale:jataka_quails_net" "A flock of quails escapes the fowler by a trick their leader teaches: when the net falls, all thrust their heads through the mesh and rise together to carry it off, then drop it on a thornbush and slip free. This works until two quails quarrel over who jostled whom; while they bicker, the net falls and the fowler takes them all. Moral: in unity is safety; in discord, ruin. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_quails_net fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_quails_net unity @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_quails_net discord @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_quails_net bodhisattva @related_to
ln tale:jataka_quails_net tale:panchatantra_doves_net @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_quails_net"

def "tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare" "A hare dozing under a tree is startled by the thud of a falling fruit and, certain the earth is breaking apart, bolts in terror. The other hares flee with it, then the deer, the boar, the buffalo, the elephants, until all the beasts stampede toward the sea. A wise lion halts them, traces the panic to its source, finds only a fallen fruit, and turns the herd safely home. Moral: trace a rumor to its root before you flee it. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare panic @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare rumor @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare investigation @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare bodhisattva @related_to
ln tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_sky_falling_hare"

def "tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise" "A tortoise too fond of talking befriends two geese, who offer to fly it to their mountain home gripping a stick in its mouth, on the one condition that it stay silent. Passing over a town, it is jeered by children and, stung, opens its mouth to retort, loses its hold, and falls. Moral: the one who cannot hold his tongue brings about his own fall. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise foolish_speech @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise restraint @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise tale:panchatantra_talkative_turtle @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_talkative_tortoise"

def "tale:jataka_valahassa_horse" "Merchants shipwrecked on an island are welcomed by beautiful women who are in truth man-eating ogresses. The Bodhisattva, born as a great flying horse, comes offering rescue and cries that all who wish to be saved must hold fast to him and never look back at the island's charms. Those who cling firmly are borne to safety; those who turn to the ogresses' calls fall and are devoured. Moral: from temptation, hold fast and do not look back. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_valahassa_horse fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_valahassa_horse temptation @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_valahassa_horse resolve @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_valahassa_horse bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_valahassa_horse"

def "tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan" "Two caravan-leaders cross a desert. Goblins disguised as travelers coming from ahead, clothes soaked and telling of plentiful water, persuade the foolish leader to throw away his water-casks; stranded and parched, his company is destroyed. The wise leader, the Bodhisattva, distrusts the too-easy story, keeps his water, and brings his people through alive. Moral: distrust the convenient tale; keep what sustains you until you know. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan prudence @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan caution @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_wise_foolish_caravan"

def "tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon" "A hare, the Bodhisattva, vows to give alms and, having only grass to offer, resolves to give his own body. When a beggar — the god Sakka in disguise — asks for food, the hare shakes itself to spare any insects in its fur and leaps into the fire, which does not burn it. Honoring the selfless gift, Sakka paints the hare's image upon the moon for all ages to see. Moral: the purest gift is the gift of oneself. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon generosity @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon self_sacrifice @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_wise_hare_moon"

def "tale:jataka_wise_valuer" "A king replaces his honest valuer with a greedy courtier who, to please the king, undervalues a merchant's horses at a measure of rice. Asked then what all the king's city is worth, the new valuer — coached by the Bodhisattva — solemnly prices the whole realm at that same measure of rice, shaming the king before his court into restoring the honest man. Moral: a crooked measure, carried to its end, condemns itself. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_wise_valuer fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_wise_valuer honesty @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_valuer justice @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_wise_valuer bodhisattva @related_to
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_wise_valuer"

def "tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion" "A woodpecker, hearing a lion choke on a bone, props its jaws open with a stick and draws the bone out. Later, in want, it asks the lion for some small kindness; the lion answers that the woodpecker should count itself rewarded enough for having put its head in a lion's mouth and lived. Moral: from the wicked, count mere survival as reward. — Jataka tale"
ln tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion fable sys:is_a
ln tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion ingratitude @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion prudence @illustrates
ln tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion bodhisattva @related_to
ln tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion tale:aesop_wolf_crane @parallels
set.add name="ontology.jataka_fables" id="tale:jataka_woodpecker_lion"

def "tale:jefferies_after_london" "After London (Richard Jefferies) - long after the fall, England has drowned in forest, with a poisoned lake where the great city stood, reverted to a feudal wild."
ln tale:jefferies_after_london fnty:science_fiction sys:is_a
ln tale:jefferies_after_london post_apocalypse sys:refers_to
ln tale:jefferies_after_london ruined_civilization sys:refers_to
ln tale:jefferies_after_london the_wild_future calc:associated_with

def "tale:kancil_crocodiles" "Wishing to cross the river to a fruit orchard, Kancil tells the crocodiles that the king has ordered a feast and he must first count them all. He bids them line up nose to tail across the water, then hops from back to back as he 'counts,' and skips ashore on the far bank before they understand the trick. Moral: wit turns even one's hunters into a bridge. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_crocodiles fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_crocodiles wit @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_crocodiles strategy @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_crocodiles tale:jataka_monkey_crocodile @parallels
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_crocodiles"

def "tale:kancil_escape_reverse" "Caught and bound for the cooking pot, Kancil pretends to dread one fate above all and begs not to be flung into the thorn thicket — anything but that. His captor, wishing to punish him most, hurls him straight into the thorns, where the nimble mouse-deer lands unhurt and darts away. Moral: let your enemy's spite carry you exactly where you wish to go. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_escape_reverse fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_escape_reverse cunning @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_escape_reverse reverse_psychology @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_escape_reverse"

def "tale:kancil_snail_race" "A snail, challenged to a race by the boastful Kancil, secretly posts cousins all along the course. Each time Kancil calls out, a snail answers from just ahead, until Kancil runs himself to exhaustion and finds a snail already at the finish. Moral: cleverness and teamwork can outrun raw speed. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_snail_race fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_snail_race cunning @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_snail_race cooperation @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_snail_race tale:aesop_tortoise_hare @parallels
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_snail_race"

def "tale:kancil_sticky_figure" "Raiding a farmer's cucumber patch, Kancil meets a silent human-shaped figure smeared with sticky sap set there to guard it. Insulted by its silence, he strikes it — and is held fast, fist after fist, until he is stuck all over and caught. Moral: it is pride and temper, not the trap, that truly bind us. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_sticky_figure fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_sticky_figure pride @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_sticky_figure temper @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_sticky_figure"

def "tale:kancil_tiger_kings_sash" "Cornered by a hungry tiger, Kancil points to a brilliantly coiled python and says it is the king's royal sash, which he has been charged to guard, and dares the tiger to try it on. The tiger wraps it round himself; the python crushes him, and Kancil slips away. Moral: a bold lie, well placed, turns a foe's greed against him. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_tiger_kings_sash fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_tiger_kings_sash cunning @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_tiger_kings_sash bluff @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_tiger_kings_sash"

def "tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile" "A man frees a crocodile stranded far from water, and the ungrateful beast at once seizes him and means to eat him. They put the case to Kancil, who professes not to understand and asks the crocodile to show exactly how it was trapped. The crocodile climbs back into the snare to demonstrate — and Kancil tells the man to leave it there and go home. Moral: let the ingrate re-enact its own trap, and justice does itself. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile justice @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile ingratitude @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile"

def "tale:kancil_well_escape" "Fallen into a deep pit he cannot climb, Kancil waits until a tiger passes, then cries that the sky is about to fall and only the pit is safe. The frightened tiger leaps in beside him; Kancil scrambles up onto the tiger's back and out of the pit, leaving the great beast trapped below. Moral: a clever word can make your captor your stepping-stone. — Sang Kancil (Malay folklore)"
ln tale:kancil_well_escape fable sys:is_a
ln tale:kancil_well_escape cunning @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_well_escape strategy @illustrates
ln tale:kancil_well_escape tale:aesop_fox_goat_well @parallels
set.add name="ontology.kancil_tales" id="tale:kancil_well_escape"

def "tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste" "(Les Animaux malades de la peste) A plague ravages the beasts, and they resolve that the guiltiest must be sacrificed to appease heaven. The lion, fox, and other predators confess great crimes and are excused with flattery; but the ass, who once ate a little grass from a meadow not his own, is condemned and put to death. Moral: the court will paint you white or black according to your power. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste injustice @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste hypocrisy @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste power @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_animaux_peste"

def "tale:lafontaine_berger_mer" "(Le Berger et la Mer) A shepherd, tempted by the calm sea and tales of profit, sells his flock to trade by ship — and loses all in a storm. Back at his shrunken flock, he hears the sea murmur invitingly once more, and answers that her smooth face wants his last coins now, and shall not have them. Moral: once burned by the smiling sea, keep to the trade you know. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_berger_mer fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_berger_mer caution @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_berger_mer contentment @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_berger_mer"

def "tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin" "(Le Chat, la Belette et le petit Lapin) A rabbit returns to find a weasel has seized his burrow; unable to settle the quarrel, the two agree to submit it to a fat, pious-seeming cat as judge. Bidding them come closer so his old ears may hear, the cat seizes and devours them both. Moral: never trust the powerful to arbitrate your dispute. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin arbitration @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin deception @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin"

def "tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau" "(Le Chêne et le Roseau) The oak pities the reed that bows to every breeze and boasts of its own strength against the storm. When the great wind comes, the reed bends and survives, while the proud oak is torn up by the roots. Moral: yielding outlasts rigid strength. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau adaptability @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau humility @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau tale:aesop_oak_reed @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_chene_roseau"

def "tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi" "(La Cigale et la Fourmi) The cicada, having sung all summer, finds itself starving when the cold wind comes and begs a loan of grain from the ant. The ant, who toiled while the cicada sang, asks what it did all summer and tells it to go and dance now. Moral: provide in plenty for the season of want. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi prudence @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi foresight @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi tale:aesop_ant_grasshopper @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_cigale_fourmi"

def "tale:lafontaine_cochet_chat_souriceau" "(Le Cochet, le Chat et le Souriceau) A young mouse, new to the world, runs home to tell his mother of a gentle, fluffy creature he longed to befriend, and a brutal, crested monster he fled in terror. The mother explains: the soft one was the cat, his deadliest foe; the fearsome one only the harmless cockerel. Moral: do not judge by the face; the gentlest look may be the most dangerous. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_cochet_chat_souriceau fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_cochet_chat_souriceau appearance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_cochet_chat_souriceau"

def "tale:lafontaine_corbeau_aigle" "(Le Corbeau voulant imiter l'Aigle) Watching an eagle carry off a lamb, a crow tries the same feat on a great ram, but its claws only tangle in the thick fleece, and the shepherd takes it captive for his children's plaything. Moral: measure your strength before you copy the mighty. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_aigle fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_aigle overreach @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_aigle tale:aesop_tortoise_eagle @parallels
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_corbeau_aigle"

def "tale:lafontaine_corbeau_renard" "(Le Corbeau et le Renard) A crow perched with cheese in its beak is flattered by a fox praising its beauty and voice. It opens its beak to sing, drops the cheese, and the fox seizes it, observing that every flatterer lives at the expense of those who heed him. Moral: flatterers feed on the vanity of their listeners. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_renard fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_renard flattery @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_corbeau_renard tale:aesop_fox_crow @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_corbeau_renard"

def "tale:lafontaine_deux_pigeons" "(Les Deux Pigeons) Two devoted pigeons live as one, until one, restless, flies off to see the world. Storm, snare, hawk, and a boy's sling batter the wanderer, who limps home at last to swear that love and the home roof outweigh all the world's adventures. Moral: the heart that loves needs travel no farther than home. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_deux_pigeons fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_deux_pigeons love @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_deux_pigeons contentment @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_deux_pigeons"

def "tale:lafontaine_gland_citrouille" "(Le Gland et la Citrouille) A countryman thinks God blundered to hang tiny acorns on mighty oaks and great pumpkins on slender vines; dozing beneath an oak, he is woken by a falling acorn on his nose, and reflects that had it been a pumpkin he would have fared far worse. Moral: the design of things is wiser than our second-guessing. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_gland_citrouille fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_gland_citrouille humility @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_gland_citrouille"

def "tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf" "(La Grenouille qui veut se faire aussi grosse que le Bœuf) A frog, admiring the bulk of an ox, swells itself to match it, straining larger and larger until it bursts. Moral: the small who ape the great destroy themselves. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf vanity @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf hubris @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf tale:aesop_frog_ox @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_grenouille_boeuf"

def "tale:lafontaine_grenouille_rat" "(La Grenouille et le Rat) A treacherous frog offers to host a rat across the marsh and ties the rat's foot to her own, meaning to drag him under and drown him. As they struggle, a kite swoops and seizes the pair, dining on both. Moral: he who plots a pit for another often falls in beside him. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_rat fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_rat treachery @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_grenouille_rat comeuppance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_grenouille_rat"

def "tale:lafontaine_heron" "(Le Héron) A heron, too dainty to eat the fish that pass, lets them go in hope of finer fare; when the river empties he is glad to swallow a small snail at last. Moral: the over-particular are left with the scraps. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_heron fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_heron fastidiousness @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_heron opportunity @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_heron tale:aesop_heron @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_heron"

def "tale:lafontaine_laboureur_enfants" "(Le Laboureur et ses Enfants) A dying farmer tells his sons a treasure is hidden in the field; they dig it over and over and find no gold, but the well-turned soil yields a rich harvest. Moral: labor itself is the treasure. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_laboureur_enfants fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_laboureur_enfants diligence @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_laboureur_enfants effort @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_laboureur_enfants"

def "tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot" "(La Laitière et le Pot au lait) Perrette, carrying milk to market, builds in her mind a fortune of eggs, chickens, a pig, a cow and calf, until, leaping for joy at the thought, she spills the milk and loses all. Moral: do not build on profits not yet in hand. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot overconfidence @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot daydreaming @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_laitiere_pot"

def "tale:lafontaine_lievre_grenouilles" "(Le Lièvre et les Grenouilles) A hare, brooding on his own timid life, despairs that no creature is more fearful than he — until, walking to the pond, he sees the frogs leap away in greater terror of him, and takes heart that there is always someone more afraid. Moral: however timid you are, you may yet be someone's terror. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_grenouilles fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_grenouilles perspective @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_grenouilles tale:aesop_hares_frogs @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_lievre_grenouilles"

def "tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue" "(Le Lièvre et la Tortue) Sure of his speed, the hare lets the tortoise start and lingers along the way; the tortoise never stops, and the hare reaches the post too late to win. Moral: there is no use in running; one must set out in good time. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue perseverance @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue complacency @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue tale:aesop_tortoise_hare @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_lievre_tortue"

def "tale:lafontaine_lion_moucheron" "(Le Lion et le Moucheron) A tiny gnat defies the lion, stings him where his claws cannot reach, and drives him to exhaust himself in fury, then trumpets its victory — only to be caught and killed in a spider's web. Moral: the least foe may humble the greatest, and the proudest victor may fall to a trifle. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_moucheron fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_moucheron hubris @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_moucheron vigilance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_lion_moucheron"

def "tale:lafontaine_lion_rat" "(Le Lion et le Rat) A lion spares a rat that fell into its paws; later, caught in a hunter's net, the lion is freed when the rat gnaws the meshes through. Moral: patience and small help accomplish what force and rage cannot. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_rat fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_rat gratitude @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_rat patience @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_rat tale:aesop_lion_mouse @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_lion_rat"

def "tale:lafontaine_lion_vieux" "(Le Lion devenu vieux) The lion, once dreaded king of beasts, grows old and feeble, and those he ruled come to take their revenge: the horse kicks him, the wolf bites, the bull gores. But the deepest wound is the ass's kick — to be insulted by the lowliest is the bitterest fall of all. Moral: outlive your strength, and even cowards will spurn you. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_vieux fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_vieux power @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_lion_vieux mortality @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_lion_vieux"

def "tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau" "(Le Loup et l'Agneau) A wolf accuses a lamb drinking downstream of muddying its water and of slanders the lamb could never have committed, then eats it without further trial. Moral: might makes right; the powerful need no true reason. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau injustice @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau tyranny @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau tale:aesop_wolf_lamb @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_loup_agneau"

def "tale:lafontaine_loup_berger" "(Le Loup devenu Berger) A wolf, finding the flock too well guarded, dresses as the shepherd to lure the sheep away, but when he tries to speak the part his howl betrays him and he is undone in his disguise. Moral: a villain's nature breaks through his borrowed costume. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_berger fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_berger deception @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_berger disguise @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_berger tale:aesop_wolf_sheeps_clothing @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_loup_berger"

def "tale:lafontaine_loup_chien" "(Le Loup et le Chien) A gaunt wolf envies a plump house-dog's easy life until it spots the bald ring the collar has worn on his neck. Learning the price is a chain, the wolf runs back to the woods, hungry and free. Moral: no comfort is worth the loss of liberty. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_chien fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_chien freedom @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_chien independence @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_chien tale:aesop_dog_wolf @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_loup_chien"

def "tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne" "(Le Loup et la Cigogne) A stork removes a bone from a choking wolf's throat and asks for the promised reward; the wolf answers that her reward is having drawn her neck out of his jaws alive. Moral: from the wicked, count it gain merely to escape unharmed. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne ingratitude @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne prudence @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne tale:aesop_wolf_crane @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_loup_cigogne"

def "tale:lafontaine_meunier_fils_ane" "(Le Meunier, son Fils et l'Âne) A miller and his son drive their donkey to market, but every passer-by faults how they manage it: ride neither, both, one, or carry it — and trying to please each in turn, they end carrying the donkey on a pole and are laughed at by all. Moral: he who tries to please everyone pleases no one. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_meunier_fils_ane fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_meunier_fils_ane indecision @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_meunier_fils_ane"

def "tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron" "(La Mort et le Bûcheron) A poor woodcutter, bowed under his faggots and his troubles, cries out for Death to come; when Death appears, he asks only for help to load the wood back on his shoulders. Moral: however wretched, we would rather suffer than die. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron mortality @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron fear @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron tale:aesop_old_man_death @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_mort_bucheron"

def "tale:lafontaine_mouche_coche" "(La Mouche et le Coche) As a coach strains up a steep, sandy hill, a fly buzzes about the horses, stinging, settling, fussing everywhere, and when the coach at last tops the rise the fly claims the whole credit for the labour. Moral: the meddler who bustles takes the credit for work that was never his. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_mouche_coche fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_mouche_coche meddling @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_mouche_coche vanity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_mouche_coche"

def "tale:lafontaine_poule_oeufs_or" "(La Poule aux œufs d'or) A man owns a hen that lays a golden egg each day, and, certain a treasure lies within, kills it to seize all at once, finding it the same as any other hen. Moral: greed for everything loses what one has. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_poule_oeufs_or fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_poule_oeufs_or greed @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_poule_oeufs_or tale:aesop_golden_goose @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_poule_oeufs_or"

def "tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs" "(Le Rat de ville et le Rat des champs) A city rat feasts its country cousin on rich leavings, but the meal is broken by the noise of intruders and the terror of being caught. The country rat departs, preferring a plain dinner that no fear disturbs. Moral: a humble meal in peace beats a feast in fear. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs contentment @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs simplicity @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs tale:aesop_town_country_mouse @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_rat_ville_champs"

def "tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc" "(Le Renard et le Bouc) A fox and a goat descend a well to drink; trapped, the cunning fox persuades the goat to brace itself so the fox can climb out on its horns, then leaves it below with advice to think before it acts. Moral: look before you leap, and beware the counsel of the cornered. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc caution @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc cunning @related_to
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc tale:aesop_fox_goat_well @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_renard_bouc"

def "tale:lafontaine_renard_raisins" "(Le Renard et les Raisins) A fox, unable to reach grapes hanging high on the vine, declares them too green and fit only for fools, and moves on. Moral: we scorn what we cannot obtain. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_raisins fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_raisins rationalization @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_renard_raisins tale:aesop_fox_grapes @adapts
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_renard_raisins"

def "tale:lafontaine_savetier_financier" "(Le Savetier et le Financier) A poor cobbler sings all day, to the envy of a rich financier who cannot sleep for his cares. The financier gives him a purse of gold; but the cobbler, suddenly anxious for his hoard, loses his sleep and his songs — and returns the money to buy back his cheerful poverty. Moral: peace and a glad heart are worth more than gold. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_savetier_financier fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_savetier_financier contentment @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_savetier_financier wealth @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_savetier_financier"

def "tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards" "(La Tortue et les Deux Canards) A tortoise, weary of her home, has two ducks carry her aloft on a stick gripped in her mouth, on the condition she keep silent. As folk below marvel at the flying tortoise calling her a queen, she cannot resist answering — opens her mouth, and falls. Moral: vanity and a loose tongue bring the high low. — Jean de La Fontaine"
ln tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards fable sys:is_a
ln tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards foolish_speech @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards vanity @illustrates
ln tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards tale:panchatantra_talkative_turtle @parallels
set.add name="ontology.lafontaine_fables" id="tale:lafontaine_tortue_canards"

def "tale:lane_mizora" "Mizora (Mary Bradley Lane) - a subterranean world of women alone, who long ago bred men out of existence and live by science; one of the earliest feminist utopias."
