def "tale:nasreddin_age_forty" "Asked his age, the Hodja answers, 'Forty.' Years later, asked again, he gives the same reply. 'But you said forty long ago!' 'A grown man,' he declares, 'stands by his word.' Moral: consistency held past all reason is only stubbornness in disguise. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_age_forty fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_age_forty stubbornness @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_age_forty wit @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_age_forty"

def "tale:nasreddin_do_you_know" "Mounting the pulpit, the Hodja asks if the congregation knows what he is about to say. 'No,' they answer; 'then what use is it to preach to such ignorant folk?' and he leaves. Next time they answer 'Yes'; 'then you have no need of me.' The third time, half say yes and half no — 'then let those who know tell those who do not.' Moral: a clever evasion can answer any question but the real one. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_do_you_know fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_do_you_know wit @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_do_you_know evasion @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_do_you_know"

def "tale:nasreddin_eat_my_coat" "Turned away from a feast in his shabby clothes, the Hodja returns in a splendid fur coat and is shown to the place of honor. He dips his sleeve into the dishes, urging, 'Eat, my coat, eat' — for plainly it was the coat, not the man, that was invited. Moral: a world that honors the garment deserves to feed it. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_eat_my_coat fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_eat_my_coat hypocrisy @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_eat_my_coat appearance @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_eat_my_coat"

def "tale:nasreddin_lost_key" "Neighbors find the Hodja searching the ground beneath a street lamp and join the hunt for his lost key. When they ask where exactly he dropped it, he says inside his house — but the light is so much better out here. Moral: we look for answers where it is easy, not where they are. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_lost_key fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_lost_key folly @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_lost_key self_deception @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_lost_key"

def "tale:nasreddin_moon_in_well" "Seeing the moon's reflection trembling at the bottom of a well, the Hodja is sure it has fallen in and hauls on a rope and hook to rescue it. The hook catches, he heaves with all his might, the rope snaps, and he tumbles flat — but, seeing the moon back in the sky, he rejoices that he saved it just in time. Moral: a fool will take the credit even for the work of the heavens. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_moon_in_well fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_moon_in_well folly @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_moon_in_well self_deception @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_moon_in_well"

def "tale:nasreddin_neighbor_donkey" "A neighbor comes to borrow the Hodja's donkey, and the Hodja says it is not at home — just as the donkey brays loudly from the stable. 'But Hodja, I can hear it!' 'What kind of man are you,' replies the Hodja, offended, 'to take the word of a donkey over a grey-bearded man?' Moral: indignation is the last refuge of a poor excuse. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_neighbor_donkey fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_neighbor_donkey wit @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_neighbor_donkey pretext @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_neighbor_donkey"

def "tale:nasreddin_pot_that_died" "The Hodja borrows a pot and returns it with a small pot inside, saying it gave birth; the lender gladly keeps both. Next time the Hodja keeps the pot, and reports it has died. 'A pot cannot die!' cries the lender. 'You believed it could give birth,' says the Hodja, 'so believe it can die.' Moral: greed that swallows the absurd must swallow the loss as well. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_pot_that_died fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_pot_that_died wit @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_pot_that_died greed @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_pot_that_died"

def "tale:nasreddin_quilt_quarrel" "Hearing a commotion in the street one night, the Hodja wraps himself in his quilt and goes out to look; thieves snatch the quilt from his shoulders and run off. His wife asks what the noise was about. 'It was about our quilt,' he says; 'once the quilt was gone, the quarrel was over.' Moral: take away the prize and the dispute dissolves. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_quilt_quarrel fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_quilt_quarrel irony @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_quilt_quarrel"

def "tale:nasreddin_salt_and_wool" "The Hodja's donkey, laden with salt, lies down in the river and rises lighter as the salt dissolves, and the Hodja scolds its cunning. Next day he loads it with wool; the beast lies down again, the wool soaks heavy, and it staggers up under double the weight. Moral: a trick that worked once will betray the one who repeats it without thought. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_salt_and_wool fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_salt_and_wool folly @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_salt_and_wool context @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_salt_and_wool"

def "tale:nasreddin_sawing_branch" "Sitting on a branch and sawing it off between himself and the trunk, the Hodja is warned by a passerby that he will fall. He ignores the advice, and of course down he comes. Running after the stranger, he begs to know the hour of his death, since the man so clearly foretold the future. Moral: a lucky guess is not wisdom, and a fool mistakes the two. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_sawing_branch fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_sawing_branch folly @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_sawing_branch"

def "tale:nasreddin_smell_of_food" "A poor man eating dry bread by a cookshop is accused by the owner of stealing the savor of the food and dragged before Nasreddin to pay. The Hodja shakes a purse of coins and tells the cook to take the sound of the money as payment for the smell of the food. Moral: an imaginary debt deserves an imaginary coin. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_smell_of_food fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_smell_of_food wit @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_smell_of_food justice @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_smell_of_food"

def "tale:nasreddin_soup_of_soup" "A villager brings the Hodja a rabbit and is feasted. Then the man's friends arrive expecting the same, then friends of those friends, until the Hodja sets before the latest crowd a pot of plain hot water, calling it 'the soup of the soup of the rabbit.' Moral: a favor stretched too thin becomes nothing at all. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_soup_of_soup fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_soup_of_soup wit @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_soup_of_soup freeloading @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_soup_of_soup"

def "tale:nasreddin_teach_donkey_read" "Ordered by a powerful ruler to teach a donkey to read, the Hodja asks for many years and a purse of gold, then trains the beast to flip the pages of a book with its tongue in search of hidden oats. 'By the time the lesson is done,' he reasons, 'either the king, the donkey, or I will be dead.' Moral: when refusal is fatal, buy time and let fate decide. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_teach_donkey_read fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_teach_donkey_read cunning @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_teach_donkey_read prudence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_teach_donkey_read"

def "tale:nasreddin_you_are_right_too" "Hearing a plaintiff, the Hodja says, 'You are right'; hearing the defendant, 'You are right.' When his wife protests that both cannot be right at once, he considers and says, 'You know — you are right too.' Moral: the wish to please everyone settles nothing. — Nasreddin Hodja"
ln tale:nasreddin_you_are_right_too fable sys:is_a
ln tale:nasreddin_you_are_right_too indecision @illustrates
ln tale:nasreddin_you_are_right_too wit @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.nasreddin_tales" id="tale:nasreddin_you_are_right_too"

def "tale:native_coyote_and_death" "When the people first debate whether the dead should return, Coyote argues that they should stay gone, lest the world grow too crowded, and his word prevails. But when his own child soon dies, Coyote pleads to bring the dead back after all — and is told it is too late, for the law he urged is now fixed. Moral: the rule you press on others will bind you in your own grief. — Native American (Coyote tale)"
ln tale:native_coyote_and_death folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_coyote_and_death consequence @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_and_death mortality @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_and_death origin @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_coyote_and_death"

def "tale:native_coyote_bungling_host" "Coyote is fed by hosts who each draw food by some marvel — Bear from his own paws, Kingfisher diving through ice, Deer from his nose. Proud, Coyote invites them back and tries to copy each feat himself, only to burn, bruise, and gash himself with nothing to show. Moral: aping another's gift without his nature brings only injury. — Native American (Coyote tale)"
ln tale:native_coyote_bungling_host folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_coyote_bungling_host imitation @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_bungling_host folly @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_bungling_host tale:china_handan_walk @parallels
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_coyote_bungling_host"

def "tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars" "The Creator gives Coyote the task of placing the stars in careful order across the night. Impatient and bored with the slow work, Coyote flings the whole basket of stars into the sky at once, and that is why most stars lie scattered without pattern, in the great careless spill we call the Milky Way. Moral: haste leaves its disorder written across the heavens. — Native American (Coyote tale)"
ln tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars haste @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars origin @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars stars @related_to
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_coyote_scatters_stars"

def "tale:native_coyote_steals_fire" "When people shiver through winter without fire, Coyote climbs to the mountain where the Fire Beings guard their flame and snatches a burning brand. Pursued, he passes the fire to Squirrel, whose tail curls from the heat, then to Frog, who loses his tail, then into the wood itself, where fire has hidden ever since, to be coaxed out by rubbing. Moral: a gift won for all may cost the givers dearly, and leaves its mark on the world. — Native American (Coyote tale)"
ln tale:native_coyote_steals_fire folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_coyote_steals_fire trickster @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_steals_fire origin @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_steals_fire fire @related_to
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_coyote_steals_fire"

def "tale:native_coyote_tug_of_war" "Mocked by a buffalo and threatened by a great fish, the small Coyote challenges each to a tug-of-war with a long rope, slyly tying the two ends to the buffalo and the fish on opposite sides of a hill so that, hidden between, he seems to match them both. The two haul against each other to exhaustion while Coyote rests. Moral: set the strong against the strong, and the weak need not strain at all. — Native American (Coyote tale)"
ln tale:native_coyote_tug_of_war folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_coyote_tug_of_war cunning @illustrates
ln tale:native_coyote_tug_of_war strategy @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_coyote_tug_of_war"

def "tale:native_raven_fresh_water" "All the world's fresh water is kept by one selfish being who will share none. Raven visits as a guest, drinks his fill in secret until he can hold no more, and flies off; as he escapes through the smoke-hole he spills the water across the land, and wherever the drops fall the rivers, lakes, and springs begin. Moral: what one would keep for himself, the trickster scatters into the world's abundance. — Native American (Pacific Northwest)"
ln tale:native_raven_fresh_water folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_raven_fresh_water trickster @illustrates
ln tale:native_raven_fresh_water origin @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_raven_fresh_water"

def "tale:native_raven_steals_light" "The world lies in darkness because a selfish chief hoards the daylight in a carved box. Raven turns himself into a pine needle, is swallowed by the chief's daughter, and is reborn as her child; petted and indulged, the child cries until he is given the box to play with, then takes wing as Raven and frees the sun and stars into the sky. Moral: light hoarded for one is, by cunning, set free for all. — Native American (Pacific Northwest)"
ln tale:native_raven_steals_light folktale sys:is_a
ln tale:native_raven_steals_light trickster @illustrates
ln tale:native_raven_steals_light origin @illustrates
ln tale:native_raven_steals_light light @related_to
set.add name="ontology.native_american_tales" id="tale:native_raven_steals_light"

def "tale:obrien_diamond_lens" "The Diamond Lens (Fitz-James O'Brien) - through a perfect microscope a man beholds, and hopelessly loves, a living being within a single drop of water; the infinite small."
ln tale:obrien_diamond_lens fnty:science_fiction sys:is_a
ln tale:obrien_diamond_lens the_microscopic sys:refers_to
ln tale:obrien_diamond_lens obsession sys:refers_to
ln tale:obrien_diamond_lens the_infinite_small calc:associated_with

def "tale:odoevsky_4338" "The Year 4338 (Vladimir Odoevsky) - a Russian dreams of the forty-fourth century, of climate turned to use and of households joined by magnetic telegraphs that carry news and gossip; the internet, foreseen."
ln tale:odoevsky_4338 fnty:science_fiction sys:is_a
ln tale:odoevsky_4338 future_utopia sys:refers_to
ln tale:odoevsky_4338 prophecy sys:refers_to
ln tale:odoevsky_4338 the_future calc:associated_with
ln tale:odoevsky_4338 tale:robida_twentieth_century calc:associated_with

def "tale:orwell_1984" "Nineteen Eighty-Four (George Orwell) — Big Brother, Newspeak, and doublethink; a boot stamping on a human face, forever, and the last free thought erased."
ln tale:orwell_1984 fnty:science_fiction sys:is_a
ln tale:orwell_1984 dystopia sys:refers_to
ln tale:orwell_1984 totalitarianism sys:refers_to
ln tale:orwell_1984 surveillance calc:associated_with
ln tale:orwell_1984 nar:rebellion calc:associated_with
ln tale:orwell_1984 emo:fear has_emotion
ln tale:orwell_1984 tale:zamyatin_we calc:associated_with

def "tale:oshikawa_undersea" "The Undersea Warship (Oshikawa Shunro) — Japan's answer to Verne; a secret super-submarine and an age of scientific adventure, written at the dawn of Japanese SF."
ln tale:oshikawa_undersea fnty:science_fiction sys:is_a
ln tale:oshikawa_undersea the_machine sys:refers_to
ln tale:oshikawa_undersea adventure sys:refers_to
ln tale:oshikawa_undersea exploration calc:associated_with
ln tale:oshikawa_undersea tale:verne_voyages calc:associated_with

def "tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal" "A jackal, fleeing dogs, tumbles into a vat of indigo and emerges dyed blue. Unrecognizable, he proclaims himself a heaven-sent king and rules the awed beasts, until one evening the howling of distant jackals stirs him to howl in answer; his own cry betrays his kind, and the beasts fall upon him. Moral: a false identity is undone by one's own nature. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal pretension @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal false_identity @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal"

def "tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose" "A Brahmin's wife leaves a mongoose to guard her sleeping baby. A cobra approaches and the loyal mongoose kills it, then greets the returning mother with a bloodied mouth. Seeing the blood and assuming the worst, she strikes the mongoose dead in haste — then finds the child safe beside the slain snake. Moral: act in haste and repent forever. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose haste @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose regret @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose loyalty @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_brahmin_mongoose"

def "tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots" "A poor Brahmin, given a pot of rice-gruel, hangs it by his bed and dreams of selling it to buy goats, then cows, then a rich marriage and sons — and imagining himself scolding his future wife, he kicks out in his daydream, shatters the pot, and is left with nothing. Moral: do not feast on profits not yet earned. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots daydreaming @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots overconfidence @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots tale:aesop_milkmaid_pail @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_brahmin_pots"

def "tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger" "A kindly Brahmin frees a tiger begging release from its cage; once out, the ungrateful beast means to eat him. They agree to ask three witnesses — a tree, a buffalo, a road — who all say humans repay good with ill. At last a jackal feigns confusion and asks the tiger to show how it was caged; the tiger climbs back in to demonstrate, and the jackal latches the door. Moral: cleverness must rescue kindness from the jaws of ingratitude. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger ingratitude @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger justice @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger tale:kancil_ungrateful_crocodile @parallels
ln tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger tale:arabian_fisherman_jinni @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_brahmin_tiger"

def "tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment" "A partridge returns to find a hare has taken over its home; unable to agree whose it is, the two seek out a cat sitting by the river in the pose of a holy ascetic, eyes half closed, reciting scripture. Bidding the disputants come near his failing ears to plead, the pious-seeming cat seizes them both and eats them. Moral: do not lay your quarrel before a powerful hypocrite. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment arbitration @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment false_piety @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment tale:lafontaine_chat_belette_lapin @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_cat_judgment"

def "tale:panchatantra_crows_cobra" "A pair of crows, robbed of their young each year by a cobra that lives below their tree, devise a plan: the hen crow snatches a queen's gold necklace as she bathes and drops it into the cobra's hole. The pursuing guards kill the snake to recover the gold. Moral: what strength cannot do, a stratagem can. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_cobra fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_cobra stratagem @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_cobra ingenuity @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_crows_cobra"

def "tale:panchatantra_crows_owls" "Crows and owls are sworn enemies; the owls, who see by night, slaughter the crows in the dark. A wise old crow lets his own flock pluck his feathers and feigns being cast out, gains the owls' trust, learns their cave, and leads the crows to heap it with burning wood, destroying the owls as they sleep. Moral: in a war that cannot be won by force, win it by stratagem. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_owls fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_owls stratagem @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_crows_owls war @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_crows_owls"

def "tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin" "A washerman drapes his donkey in a leopard's skin and lets it graze by night in the fields, where farmers flee the supposed beast. All goes well until the donkey, hearing a she-donkey bray, brays in answer; the farmers know the voice, and beat it. Moral: the disguise is betrayed by the voice within. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin false_identity @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin tale:panchatantra_blue_jackal @parallels
ln tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin tale:aesop_ass_lion_skin @parallels
ln tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin tale:jataka_ass_lions_skin @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_donkey_leopard_skin"

def "tale:panchatantra_doves_net" "A flock of doves descends on scattered grain and is caught together under a hunter's net. Their king bids them not to struggle apart but to beat their wings as one; rising together, they carry off the whole net and fly to a friendly mouse, who gnaws every dove free. Moral: acting as one, the many escape what no one could alone. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_doves_net fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_doves_net unity @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_doves_net cooperation @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_doves_net tale:aesop_bundle_sticks @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_doves_net"

def "tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice" "A herd of elephants, crossing to a lake, tramples a village of mice. The mouse-king begs the elephant-king to choose another path, and he kindly does. Later, when the elephants are trapped in the hunters' ropes, the grateful mice come in their thousands by night and gnaw every elephant free. Moral: spare the small, and the small may one day save you. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice gratitude @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice reciprocity @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice tale:aesop_lion_mouse @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_elephants_mice"

def "tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king" "A king keeps a devoted pet monkey as a bodyguard. One day, as the king sleeps, a bee lands on his face; the loyal but witless monkey snatches up a sword to kill the bee and gashes the king instead. Moral: a foolish friend is more dangerous than a wise enemy. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king folly @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king friendship @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_foolish_monkey_king"

def "tale:panchatantra_four_friends" "A deer, a crow, a mouse, and a tortoise live as fast friends. When the deer is snared by a hunter, the crow scouts, the mouse gnaws the net, and they free him; when the slow tortoise is then caught, the deer decoys the hunter while the mouse cuts the second net. Moral: loyal friends, each with their gift, save one another. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_four_friends fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_four_friends friendship @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_four_friends cooperation @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_four_friends"

def "tale:panchatantra_frogs_ride_snake" "An aging frog-king, too feeble to hunt, tells a snake that he will provide it frogs to ride upon and eat, in exchange for carrying him in state — meaning to be rid of rival frogs. The snake obliges, devouring frog after frog, until none are left but the king himself, whom it eats last. Moral: he who hires his own destroyer to settle scores is eaten in the end. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_frogs_ride_snake fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_frogs_ride_snake treachery @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_frogs_ride_snake folly @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_frogs_ride_snake"

def "tale:panchatantra_hares_moon" "A herd of elephants, parched in a drought, tramples the hares' warren around a lake. The hares send a clever envoy who tells the elephant king that the Moon, whose lake this is, is enraged; showing the trembling reflection of the moon in the water as the god's own quivering anger, he frightens the elephants into leaving forever. Moral: a clever bluff can move what no force could. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_hares_moon fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_hares_moon cleverness @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_hares_moon bluff @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_hares_moon"

def "tale:panchatantra_heron_crab" "A crafty old heron, too weak to fish, tells the fish of a coming drought and offers to carry them one by one to a safe lake — eating each in turn behind a rock. When at last a crab asks to be carried, it sees the bones, grips the heron's neck in its claws, and chokes the deceiver. Moral: deceit devours others until it meets the one it cannot fool. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_heron_crab fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_heron_crab deceit @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_heron_crab greed @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_heron_crab"

def "tale:panchatantra_jackal_bowstring" "A greedy jackal finds the body of a hunter and, gnawing at the taut bowstring for the bits of meat upon it, severs it; the freed bow snaps straight and the horn-tip drives through the jackal's skull. Moral: greed that gnaws at a drawn bow is killed by it. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_bowstring fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_bowstring greed @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_jackal_bowstring"

def "tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant" "A jackal finds a dead elephant too tough to tear open, and as a lion, a tiger, and a leopard arrive each hungry for it, he plays them against one another with flattery and fear until all have gone — then opens the carcass at leisure through the soft trunk, and eats alone. Moral: where the strong contend, the cunning dine. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant cunning @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant opportunism @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant tale:aesop_lion_bear_fox @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_jackal_dead_elephant"

def "tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum" "A hungry jackal, wandering a deserted battlefield, hears a fearsome booming and trembles, thinking some great beast is near. Creeping closer, he finds only a war-drum that thunders when the wind beats a branch against it — and inside, nothing but air. Moral: the loudest threats are often the most hollow. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum empty_threats @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum courage @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum tale:aesop_mountain_labour @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_jackal_drum"

def "tale:panchatantra_lapwing_sea" "When the sea washes away the eggs a small lapwing laid too near the shore, the bird vows to dry up the whole ocean, carrying off the water beak by beak. The other birds, then mighty Garuda, are moved by such resolve to plead its cause, and the sea, fearing the gods, returns the eggs. Moral: unyielding resolve, however small, can move the vast. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_lapwing_sea fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_lapwing_sea resolve @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_lapwing_sea tale:china_yugong_mountain @parallels
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_lapwing_sea"

def "tale:panchatantra_lion_camel" "A camel strays into a lion's domain and is taken under the lion's protection, to the envy of the jackal, crow, and leopard of the court. When famine comes, the courtiers scheme: each offers the weakened lion his own body, knowing the lion will refuse — until the trusting camel offers his, and is at once taken at his word and devoured. Moral: among flatterers at court, the trusting outsider is the first meal. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_camel fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_camel treachery @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_camel flattery @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_lion_camel"

def "tale:panchatantra_lion_clever_hare" "A tyrant lion is promised one animal a day if he will stop his slaughter. When a clever hare's turn comes, it arrives late and tells the lion a rival lion bars the way; led to a well, the lion sees his own reflection, takes it for the rival, and leaps in to his death. Moral: wit can bring down brute strength. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_clever_hare fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_clever_hare wit @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_clever_hare strategy @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_lion_clever_hare"

def "tale:panchatantra_lion_foolish_donkey" "A lion's jackal lures a donkey to the lion with promises of lush pasture and a she-donkey. The lion, too eager, springs early and only stuns it, and the donkey flees; but, persuaded a second time by the same sweet words, the foolish donkey returns and is killed. The jackal, asked where the heart and ears went, says a beast that walked twice into a lion's den can have had neither. Moral: he who will not learn from one escape deserves the second jaws. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_foolish_donkey fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_foolish_donkey folly @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_lion_foolish_donkey"

def "tale:panchatantra_lion_makers" "Three learned but foolish friends find the bones of a dead lion and, to display their science, one assembles the skeleton, one clothes it in flesh and hide, and the third prepares to breathe in life. A fourth, who has only common sense, warns them and climbs a tree; they revive the lion, and it devours them. Moral: learning without judgment is deadly. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_makers fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_makers knowledge @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_lion_makers prudence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_lion_makers"

def "tale:panchatantra_mice_iron" "A merchant leaves iron scales with a friend, who later claims that mice ate the iron. The merchant says nothing, but takes the friend's son for a walk; returning alone, he reports that a hawk carried the boy off. When the friend protests that no hawk can lift a child, the merchant replies that where mice devour iron, hawks may well carry boys. The iron is promptly returned. Moral: a lie is best answered by its own logic. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_mice_iron fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_mice_iron reciprocity @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_mice_iron deceit @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_mice_iron"

def "tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile" "A monkey on a riverbank shares fruit with a crocodile until the crocodile's wife craves the monkey's heart. Lured onto the crocodile's back midstream and told the plan, the monkey calmly says he has left his heart in the tree and must fetch it; carried back, he leaps to safety. Moral: presence of mind outwits treachery. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile wit @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile betrayal @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_monkey_crocodile"

def "tale:panchatantra_monkey_wedge" "Carpenters leave a half-split log held open by a wedge. A meddlesome monkey, left alone, sits astride the log and tugs the wedge loose; the log snaps shut on him and crushes him. Moral: those who meddle in matters not their own come to grief. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_monkey_wedge fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_monkey_wedge meddling @illustrates
