set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_talkative_turtle"

def "tale:panchatantra_three_fish" "Three fish share a pool: the Far-sighted, the Quick-witted, and the Fatalist. Hearing fishermen plan to drain the pool tomorrow, the Far-sighted leaves at once by the channel; when the nets come, the Quick-witted feigns death and is thrown back; but the Fatalist, who trusted to fate and did nothing, is caught. Moral: foresight saves, wit may save, but fatalism is caught in the net. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_three_fish fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_three_fish foresight @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_three_fish prudence @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_three_fish"

def "tale:panchatantra_two_headed_bird" "A bird called Bharunda has one body and two heads. When one head finds sweet fruit and will not share, the slighted head spitefully swallows a poison fruit, saying it eats with its own mouth; the single body sickens and both heads die. Moral: division within destroys the whole. — Panchatantra (attrib. Vishnu Sharma)"
ln tale:panchatantra_two_headed_bird fable sys:is_a
ln tale:panchatantra_two_headed_bird division @illustrates
ln tale:panchatantra_two_headed_bird self_destruction @illustrates
set.add name="ontology.panchatantra_fables" id="tale:panchatantra_two_headed_bird"

